ring in Archives -- tV: Cultural Memory Perspectives Applied Beyond the Old Testament -- tWas the Maccabean Revolt the ‘First Religiously Motivated War in History’ (J. Assmann)? Exegetical, Historical and Hermeneutical Contributions to a Recent Discussion -- tMemories of the Veil: The Covenantal Contrasts in Christian- Jewish Encounter -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of References0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCultural memory is the shared reproduction and recollection of what has been learned and retained, normally treated as “the cultural heritage”. The purpose of this book, the first product of the research program Cultural Memory in Biblical Exegesis, is to study how memory is inscribed and embodied in biblical culture and its surrounding area. The essays in this volume seek to open new investigations into cultural memory in biblical and cognate studies, and to include a plethora of methods and perspectives such as the relationship between cultural memory approach and post-colonialism, globalism and epistemology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMemoryxBiblical teaching. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aCarstens, Pernille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarstens, Pernille, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChalcraft, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalcraft, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Philip R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFröhlich, Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasselbalch, Trine Bjørnung, e